{"id": "8144", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8144", "title": "December 7", "text": "December 7\n\nBULLET::::- 43 BC – Marcus Tullius Cicero is assassinated in Formia.\nBULLET::::- 574 – Byzantine Emperor Justin II, suffering recurring seizures of insanity, adopts his general Tiberius and proclaims him as \"Caesar\".\nBULLET::::- 1703 – The Great Storm of 1703, the greatest windstorm ever recorded in the southern part of Great Britain, makes landfall. Winds gust up to 120 mph, and 9,000 people die.\nBULLET::::- 1724 – Tumult of Thorn: Religious unrest is followed by the execution of nine Protestant citizens and the mayor of Thorn (Toruń) by Polish authorities.\nBULLET::::- 1732 – The Royal Opera House opens at Covent Garden, London, England.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette, arranges to enter the American military as a major general.\nBULLET::::- 1787 – Delaware becomes the first state to ratify the United States Constitution.\nBULLET::::- 1837 – The Battle of Montgomery's Tavern, the only battle of the Upper Canada Rebellion, takes place in Toronto, where the rebels are quickly defeated.\nBULLET::::- 1842 – First concert of the New York Philharmonic, founded by Ureli Corelli Hill.\nBULLET::::- 1869 – American outlaw Jesse James commits his first confirmed bank robbery in Gallatin, Missouri.\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Comparative fuel trials begin between warships and : \"Spiteful\" was the first warship powered solely by fuel oil, and the trials led to the obsolescence of coal in ships of the Royal Navy.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – World War I: The United States declares war on Austria-Hungary.\nBULLET::::- 1922 – The Parliament of Northern Ireland votes to remain a part of the United Kingdom and not unify with Southern Ireland.\nBULLET::::- 1930 – W1XAV in Boston, Massachusetts telecasts video from the CBS radio orchestra program, \"The Fox Trappers\". The telecast also includes the first television commercial in the United States, an advertisement for I.J. Fox Furriers, who sponsored the radio show.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – German-born Swiss physicist Albert Einstein is granted an American visa.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Australian cricketer Jack Fingleton becomes the first player to score centuries in four consecutive Test innings.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Attack on Pearl Harbor: The Imperial Japanese Navy carries out a surprise attack on the United States Pacific Fleet and its defending Army and Marine air forces at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. (For Japan's near-simultaneous attacks on Eastern Hemisphere targets, see December 8.)\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: British commandos conduct Operation Frankton, a raid on shipping in Bordeaux harbour.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – A fire at the Winecoff Hotel in Atlanta, Georgia kills 119 people, the deadliest hotel fire in U.S. history.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Chinese Civil War: The Government of the Republic of China moves from Nanking to Taipei, Taiwan.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Prince Rainier III of Monaco revises the principality's constitution, devolving some of his power to advisory and legislative councils.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Instant replay makes its debut during the Army-Navy football game in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States.\nBULLET::::- 1965 – Pope Paul VI and Patriarch Athenagoras I simultaneously revoke mutual excommunications that had been in place since 1054.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – The Battle of Sylhet is fought between the Pakistani military and the Mukti Bahini.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Pakistan President Yahya Khan announces the formation of a coalition government with Nurul Amin as Prime Minister and Zulfikar Ali Bhutto as Deputy Prime Minister.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – \"Apollo 17\", the last Apollo moon mission, is launched. The crew takes the photograph known as \"The Blue Marble\" as they leave the Earth.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – In Texas, Charles Brooks, Jr., becomes the first person to be executed by lethal injection in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – An Iberia Airlines Boeing 727 collides with an Aviaco DC-9 in dense fog while the two airliners are taxiing down the runway at Madrid–Barajas Airport, killing 93 people.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 1771, a British Aerospace 146-200A, crashes near Paso Robles, California, killing all 43 on board, after a disgruntled passenger shoots his ex-boss traveling on the flight, then shoots both pilots and steers the plane into the ground.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – The 6.8 Armenian earthquake shakes the northern part of the country with a maximum MSK intensity of X (\"Devastating\"), killing 25,000–50,000 and injuring 31,000–130,000.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – Long Island Rail Road shooting: Passenger Colin Ferguson murders six people and injures 19 others on the LIRR in Nassau County, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – The \"Galileo\" spacecraft arrives at Jupiter, a little more than six years after it was launched by Space Shuttle \"Atlantis\" during Mission STS-34.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – The Conservative Party of Canada is officially registered, following the merger of the Canadian Alliance and the Progressive Conservative Party of Canada.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – Rigoberto Alpizar, a passenger on American Airlines Flight 924 who allegedly claimed to have a bomb, is shot and killed by a team of U.S. federal air marshals at Miami International Airport.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – The JAXA probe Akatsuki successfully enters orbit around Venus five years after the first attempt.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Pakistan International Airlines Flight 661, a domestic passenger flight from Chitral to Islamabad, operated by ATR-42-500 crashes near Havelian, killing all 47 on board.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – The Marriage Amendment Bill to legally recognize same-sex marriages is passed in Australia's parliament.\n\nBULLET::::- 521 – Columba, Irish missionary, monk, and saint (d. 597)\nBULLET::::- 903 – Abd al-Rahman al-Sufi, Persian astronomer and author (d. 986)\nBULLET::::- 967 – Abū-Sa'īd Abul-Khayr, Persian Sufi poet (d. 1049)\nBULLET::::- 1302 – Azzone Visconti, Italian nobleman (d. 1339)\nBULLET::::- 1532 – Louis I, German nobleman and politician (d. 1605)\nBULLET::::- 1545 – Henry Stuart, English-Scottish husband of Mary, Queen of Scots (d. 1567)\nBULLET::::- 1561 – Kikkawa Hiroie, Japanese daimyō (d. 1625)\nBULLET::::- 1595 – Injo of Joseon, Korean king (d. 1649)\nBULLET::::- 1598 – Gian Lorenzo Bernini, Italian sculptor and painter (d. 1680)\nBULLET::::- 1643 – Giovanni Battista Falda, Italian architect and engraver (d. 1678)\nBULLET::::- 1637 – Bernardo Pasquini, Italian organist and composer (d. 1710)\nBULLET::::- 1764 – Claude Victor-Perrin, French general and politician (d. 1841)\nBULLET::::- 1784 – Allan Cunningham, Scottish author and poet (d. 1842)\nBULLET::::- 1791 – Ferenc Novák, Hungarian-Slovene priest and poet (d. 1836)\nBULLET::::- 1792 – Abraham Jacob van der Aa, Dutch author and academic (d. 1857)\nBULLET::::- 1801 – Johann Nestroy, Austrian actor and playwright (d. 1862)\nBULLET::::- 1810 – Josef Hyrtl, Hungarian-Austrian anatomist and biologist (d. 1894)\nBULLET::::- 1810 – Theodor Schwann, German physiologist and biologist (d. 1882)\nBULLET::::- 1823 – Leopold Kronecker, Polish-German mathematician and academic (d. 1891)\nBULLET::::- 1838 – Thomas Bent, Australian businessman and politician, 22nd Premier of Victoria (d. 1909)\nBULLET::::- 1860 – Joseph Cook, English-born Australian politician, 6th Prime Minister of Australia (d. 1947)\nBULLET::::- 1861 – Henri Mathias Berthelot, French general during World War I (d. 1931)\nBULLET::::- 1862 – Paul Adam, French author (d. 1920)\nBULLET::::- 1863 – Felix Calonder, Swiss soldier and politician, 36th President of the Swiss Confederation (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1863 – Pietro Mascagni, Italian composer and conductor (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1863 – Richard Warren Sears, American businessman, co-founded Sears (d. 1914)\nBULLET::::- 1869 – Frank Laver, Australian cricketer (d. 1919)\nBULLET::::- 1873 – Willa C